<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Coverlet configuration for tests/MTConnect.NET-Integration-Tests only.

  This is tests/coverlet.runsettings plus two product assemblies added
  to the Exclude list and the MaxCpuCount=1 serialization knob (the
  shared file no longer carries it — see below). It is applied solely
  to the integration test project (CI runs that project as its own
  `dotnet test` step with this file passed via the settings flag; the
  solution-wide run that uses tests/coverlet.runsettings no longer
  runs this project). Every other test project keeps the shared
  tests/coverlet.runsettings unchanged.

  Why the extra exclusions:
    MTConnect.NET-Integration-Tests.ClientAgentCommunicationTests
    drives the in-process Agent broker + embedded HTTP server + HTTP
    streaming client + SHDR adapter as a single timing-critical
    sample-delivery hot path. Under coverlet IL instrumentation that
    hot path is slowed enough that, on a slow shared 2-CPU CI runner,
    a Sample observation arrives after the test's 30000 ms assertion
    wait elapses (no HTTP stream timeout: the stream stays alive; the
    sample is merely late).

    Two of the assemblies on that path are also covered, faster, by
    dedicated unit suites under the shared runsettings, so dropping
    their instrumentation here loses no net (merged) coverage.
    MTConnect.NET-HTTP-Tests (and its AgentRunner support project
    MTConnect.NET-Tests-Agents) are members of MTConnect.NET.sln, so
    the solution-wide `dotnet test MTConnect.NET.sln` unit step
    discovers and runs them under the unchanged shared
    tests/coverlet.runsettings and their Cobertura is merged by
    ReportGenerator alongside this one:

    - [MTConnect.NET-Common]*  MTConnectAgentBroker observation
      buffering / sequence / delivery. By far the largest product
      assembly (all regenerated device / asset / observation types),
      so it is the dominant IL-instrumentation cost on this host.
      Covered by the MTConnect.NET-Common-Tests suite and, end to
      end, by MTConnect.NET-HTTP-Tests, which starts a real
      MTConnectAgentBroker via AgentRunner
      (tests/MTConnect.NET-Tests-Agents/AgentRunner.cs) and drives
      Probe / Current / Sample / streaming Sample through it (the
      latter pushing a live observation into the broker and asserting
      it is streamed back).
    - [MTConnect.NET-HTTP]*    embedded HTTP server stream + HTTP
      streaming client per-chunk hot loop. Covered end to end by
      MTConnect.NET-HTTP-Tests: AgentRunner spins up the real
      MTConnectHttpServer and the suite streams Current / Sample
      through MTConnectHttpClient / MTConnectHttpSampleClient
      (Clients/SampleStream.cs, Clients/Sample.cs) against it.

    MTConnect.NET-SHDR is deliberately NOT excluded, even though it sits
    ON the critical latency leg: the SHDR adapter -> broker path is part
    of the timing-sensitive sample-delivery loop this suite drives. It
    is kept instrumented anyway because the integration suite is its
    only runtime coverage — AgentRunner feeds the broker directly and
    does not exercise the SHDR adapter, and MTConnect.NET-SHDR-Tests
    covers only SHDR data-item formatting/parsing (DataItems.cs), so
    nothing else exercises ShdrIntervalAdapter / ShdrAdapterClient (the
    TCP adapter -> agent path) at runtime. SHDR is a small assembly, so
    instrumenting it costs only a small per-observation overhead on the
    hot path; excluding the two dominant-cost assemblies
    (MTConnect.NET-Common, MTConnect.NET-HTTP) returns the leg to
    near-uninstrumented latency with that small SHDR residual the only
    on-path instrumentation cost, which still leaves a large margin
    under the 30 s sample-delivery budget. The unique, non-redundant
    SHDR coverage is worth that residual.

    The integration suite remains a full behavioral end-to-end test;
    only its (redundant) coverage of MTConnect.NET-Common and
    MTConnect.NET-HTTP is dropped, and those lines are still collected
    at equal-or-greater fidelity by the faster suites whose Cobertura
    ReportGenerator merges alongside this one.

  Everything else (format, include/exclude of test assemblies,
  ExcludeByFile, ExcludeByAttribute, MaxCpuCount=1 for cross-assembly
  VSTest-host serialization) is identical to tests/coverlet.runsettings
  except that MaxCpuCount=1 now lives here only — the shared file no
  longer pins it (the integration suite is its own serial CI step; the
  shared solution-wide run lets unit assemblies parallelize). So the
  only behavioral differences for this one project are the narrowed
  instrumentation surface and the serialized VSTest host.
-->
<RunSettings>
    <RunConfiguration>
        <MaxCpuCount>1</MaxCpuCount>
    </RunConfiguration>
    <DataCollectionRunSettings>
        <DataCollectors>
            <DataCollector friendlyName="XPlat code coverage">
                <Configuration>
                    <Format>cobertura</Format>
                    <Include>[MTConnect.NET-*]*</Include>
                    <Exclude>[MTConnect.NET-*-Tests]*,[MTConnect.NET-*-Tests.*]*,[MTConnect.NET-Common]*,[MTConnect.NET-HTTP]*</Exclude>
                    <ExcludeByFile>**/*.g.cs.bak,**/TestHelpers/**/*.cs,**/TestDoubles/**/*.cs</ExcludeByFile>
                    <ExcludeByAttribute>Obsolete,GeneratedCodeAttribute,CompilerGeneratedAttribute,ExcludeFromCodeCoverageAttribute</ExcludeByAttribute>
                    <SingleHit>false</SingleHit>
                    <UseSourceLink>true</UseSourceLink>
                    <IncludeTestAssembly>false</IncludeTestAssembly>
                    <SkipAutoProps>false</SkipAutoProps>
                    <DeterministicReport>true</DeterministicReport>
                </Configuration>
            </DataCollector>
        </DataCollectors>
    </DataCollectionRunSettings>
</RunSettings>
